title: Front and Rear Mounts - Trex450 Pro V2 in A-109 Fuselage

description.text:
For mounting a Trex450 Pro V2 heli into an Align A-109 scale fuselage. The V2 version of the Trex450 Pro doesn't fit properly in the fuselage using the stock mounts, so I designed these mounts which slip over and under the plywood mounting platforms inside the fuselage. This makes it FAR easier to remove the heli from the fuselage for maintenance because only one screw, in front, is required to keep the mounts from sliding forward.  
The Rev 1 of the rear mounts doesn't have screw holes, as they are not necessary. The photo shows the version with the holes.

Made with MakerGear M2, 0.200mm layers. Best printed on-end so the layers are perpendicular to the long axis of the mount for greatest strength.  
The version in the photos was done in PLA. I also made this in nylon. I'm flying the PLA version now (during the cold months), but I'm going to switch to the nylon mounts before the weather turns hot.

They are keyed for orientation and are intended to be glued in place also. The lens is the same part for each side and is glued into each eye socket from the inside of the mask. The buckle is designed for 1" nylon web. The web loop around the head will be three layers thick through the buckle. The top web will be 2 layers thick through the buckle. Sleeves are provided to tidy up the webbing as needed. For comfort the mask edges that touch the face will probably need to be padded with whatever you may have available.

Manual Two Color Printing

How I did it on my Prusa i3 Clone single color printer. I've never used it, but I am told some slicers allow for a manual process change. But this is how I did it using Slic3r.

Note, this assumes you are comfortable modifying your printer's gcode files and that they are compatible with your printer. I suggest you try printing a small test file first, maybe a 20x20x5 mm box to see if it works for you. Or if you prefer, you can just snip the background color filament and jam the second color in after it as it starts the letters. This leaves a bit of the old color in the extruder, but it should switch before too long.

First, turn on "Verbose G-code" output under "Print Settings->Output options". This will make it easier to find the layer for switching color, then export the .gcode file as normal. Open this file with a text editor and find the comment line ";End of Layer 10". It should be around line 7281. After that line, insert the following code I found on the interwebz sompleace:

;End of Layer 10
;start pause code
G91                  ; Put in relative mode
G1 Z10 E-60          ; Lower bed by 10mm, retract 60
G90                  ; Put back in absolute mode
G1 X0 Y0             ; Zero (home) the X & Y
M0 Click To Restart  ; Pause and wait for the user
G91                  ; Put in relative mode
G1 Z-10 E60          ; Raise the bed back up 10mm, load 60
G90                  ; Put back in absolute mode
;end pause code

Save the modified .gcode file (I usually add 'pause' somewhere in the filename).

When you run the print, it should home the print head after printing the background layer (assuming .2 mm layer height) so you can eject the background color and load a new one for the text. I usually try to retract about 50 mm of filament, change to the new color then extrude about 50 mm. Then send your printer a 'RESTART'. Using OctoPrint, it should be on the main control panel. Its actually not critical if some of the old color is still in the extruder, it should start print the new one some where in that ext layer, but you don't want to switch too early, that could mess up the background.

This is a revised version of the Murloc posted by jempf788. The back foot was below-level and the center of mass was outside the footprint so it wouldn't stand up. description.text:
Designed from the ground up as a low cost, highly scalable delta printer. This printer has been built as small as carry on luggage size, up to an 18in wide print surface and is capable of larger. Approximate cost is low to mid $400 range start to finish, including electronics for a basic model. Options can push it to around $550. It's easily constructed with common tools you probably already own (hacksaw or Dremel, allen keys, soldering iron and pliers. Not a work in progress, this is a stable working printer design that has already built operational offspring. Keep in mind the design may further evolve and documentation is in progress. More information is found at http://griffinprinter.org/Griffin%20OS/index.php?board=6.0 where the complete build is documented. Including B.O.M., tips, and assembly instructions. Attribution
The J-Head mount is a modified J-Head mount by Goopyplastic (I added LED holders) and the effector is a modified Kossel (to use smaller ball ends and fit the J-head). This allows for (easier) interchangeability of Kossel Mini parts.
https://github.com/jcrocholl/kossel

No support needed. Print everything at 70% infil.
If using a heated bed, print the glass mounts with ABS.
I recommend printing the effector, effector fan and J-head mount in ABS. 3x Griffin belt tensioner

Inspired by the vein structures that carry fluids through organisms from the leaves of plants to our own circulatory systems, we created a simulation which uses physical growth principles to build sculptural, organic structures.

title: Handle for Stanley Utility XL Travel Cup 32 oz

description.text:
The STANLEY 10-01435-001 Utilty XL Travel Cup 32 oz - Green
is inexpensive (about $10) and fits automobile beverage holders well. However, it doesn't come with a handle, and because it's so large, that's annoying. This removable printable handle solves the problem. And it gives you an opportunity to add a little color to the drab green mug.

I print this in ABS in 4 pieces, each designed to rest on the Kapton-coated heated build plate without using a raft or support.
Print the handle and the OppositeSide on edge. Print the rings with the small openings for the ends of the OppositeSide upward. Trim off any sharp splots from the initial layer, using a knife. Use #4 round-head machine screws, about 3/4 inch long or cut longer ones to a maximum of about 22mm long, in the top ring. I press them through the head side (recessed) once first to clean out the hole. Twist the ring to get access to the threaded side's holes with a 4-40 tap, and tap all the way through. Assemble the pieces on the mug, tighten the screws, hold the bottom of the handle toward the mug using rubber bands, and weld the pieces with a few drops of acetone (or you can use cyanoacrylate--I've had good luck with Gorilla cyanoacrylate, doesn't harden in the bottle like others). Where the handle touches the top ring, just glue to the threaded end--otherwise you won't be able to remove the handle from the mug. I printed with about 5% infill for the prototype, and it seems strong enough that I may not do a solid version. I do think I'll seal the surfaces with an acetone vapor bath or a very quick and light brush-on coat of acetone, to prevent drips from getting inside and perhaps allowing mold, or other bad things, to grow.

title: Sphere Surface Dissection, Baseball, Tennis Ball, Math

description.text:
Printing Advice: Please use support and raft.

Looking at a baseball or a tennis ball, one wonders how to cut a spherical surface into two equal pieces. There are certainly many ways to do it, taking advantage of the spherical symmetries. Scott Elliot has some nice OpenScad code that performs such a dissection. I am looking at the project from a K-12 educational perspective. How can one dissect a spherical surface in Fusion 360 or similar 3D CAD environment?

Well, it turns out to be an appealing effort on Fusion 360, after a bit of mathematical tweaking. We can start with a hollow sphere (the result of subtracting two concentric spheres) and a cube of equal dimensions. After centering the hollow sphere and the cube, we can sketch a circle on a cube surface, whose diameter needs to be such that, if we were to make another circle of the same diameter on another orthogonal cube surface, the two circles are tangent to each other in space. A bit of algebra with the help of old Pythagoras leads to the conclusion: the circle diameter is the diameter of the outer sphere/ sqrt(2). This itself is an interesting math project for middle and secondary students.

Indeed, we need only half of that circle, plus two tangent lines for a “U” curve. Using the U curve, we could split the sphere into two pieces. These two pieces have the same outer surface, but are not exactly the same, because of the thickness. Take the half with an even thickness, construct a plane along the edge curve, sketch a 45-degree right triangle, and then perform a sweep cut along the whole path around the opening. Now, we have one half of the spherical surface (with some thickness). It takes two to make a hollow ball.
This should be an intermediate design project for 6-16 students with some guidance, as presented above. Have fun and try to come up another way to do it!

References:

  1. A brief history of the baseball. https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/a-brief-history-of-the-baseball-3685086/

  2. Baseball. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball_(ball)

  3. Elliot, Scott (2010). OpenScad code for spherical bisection, available at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3068/#files

  4. Gardner Martin. (2001). The colossal book of mathematics. New York, NY: W. W. Norton & Co.

description.text:
UPDATE: Added the a version of the duct with the same length as the OEM part.

The OEM fan duct that comes with the Anet A6 printer is not as good as it could be. It is too short and it blows the air directly on the nozzle, not on the part surface.

Having had a good experience with the Prusa i3 Mk2 -style fan duct, I designed this duct which replaces the original one. Here are the highlights:

  • It is a couple of mm longer.
  • The exit opening is on an angle directed to the print surface, not the nozzle.
  • Inner flap.
  • Better fitting.

After changing the duct I observed a fewer decrease of temperature on the hotend each time the fan is switched on.

description.text:
I didn't like the original F1 open rc servo saver design so i made a more traditional version.
print at 100% infill PLA .2mm layer.

Some setup notes:
PLA tends to stretch out over time no matter how tight you make the tolerance for the "C" part of the servo saver, so after a while you get some Wandering i recommend installing a large O-Ring over the "C" so that the PLA has some positive spring back while protecting the Servo from damage.

make sure you do not tighten down the top and bottom Counter sunk 3mm bolts you want the servo saver to have a little float to prevent the unit from binding on the upper or lower plate. Ideally it would of been better to redesign the servo saver with a metal post in the center that was Slightly taller to prevent binding but i wanted this part to fit right into the original design without additional parts. I also put a little plastic safe oil on the top and bottom screw mounts to make sure there is no binding in the servo saver. that should help in setting up the servo saver and improving the original steering.

you will need to fabricate your own servo linkage, i used an old Airplane flap adjustable linkage in mine.

description.text:
Because the gimbal on Thingiverse didn't fit my Chinese 2208 motors from AliExpress, I remeasured the gimbal and redrew one in SolidWorks.

I changed a few things, like for example the GoPro mount. I added a nice honeycomb mesh and thinned out some non-structural parts to shorten printing time. I made the motor mount higher, for extra strength and enlarged the hole for the motor for easy mounting.

I kept important dimensions so that the GoPro is still balanced out and that it stays snug during flight. Don't forget to tie the GoPro down and add a tie-wrap through the rubber balls, in case both parts seperate in mid air or as result of a crash.

I printed the gimbal with 0.2mm layer hight and with 10-20% infill. I don't know if it fits other models than a GoPro Hero 3/4
Make sure the scale is 100% and print parts bottom-down, as shown in the pictures above.

description.text:
A 360° thrust vectoring unit for 70mm EDF's.

The unit should be scalable as it originates from a smaller design, plus you have the ability to tighten the nozzle via a screw helping you with tolerances.

The ball joint has an inner diameter of 62.8 mm on the thrust tube side.

You can mount the unit normal (one servo for horizontal/pitch and the other servo for yaw movement) or tilted by 45° to one side were both servos are mixed together to achieve pitch and yaw movement (a simple elevon or delta mixer)

Required parts:

  • 2x push rods with z-bends or ballheads
  • 2x 9g servos
  • 1x ~2,5 x 8 mm wood screw

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

20-30%

Notes:

Print with two wall lines (0.8mm), for rigidity and for a smoother surface as the infill doesn't show through.

Print the parts upright without support (only the pin mount could need some support).

A finer resolution could save you some time sanding, but i only printed at .2 mm

Sanding!

You need to sand down the contacting surfaces both on the outside of the ball joint as well as on the inside of the nozzle to get rid of any layer lines and to make the assembly easy to move.

I started with 120 grit and worked my up to ~ 600 grit in a whole of 4 steps.

After I was done sanding I sprayed some PTFE dry lube onto a paper towel and rubbed over all the surfaces of the nozzle and ball joint i just sanded down to minimize friction/stiction, any other lubricant like simple oil should do.

Assembly

1: Find a fitting screw for the blocks on the side of the nozzle and drill out the holes if needed (but dont screw it in yet !)

2: Glue the pin mount to the nozzle, so it is in the center of a axis movement (e.g. yaw axis) with CA or any other glue that works good with your filament. The pin (orange) is supposed to be guided by a small piece with a slot in it (turquoise) to secure the nozzle from rotating.

3: Now carefully push the nozzle on to the ball joint until it sits in place, now screw in the screw you just picked and tighten it until you can still move the assembly easily and there is no play.
if you are afraid the nozzle is to tight to fit on the ball joint just slice in a small slot with a hot knive on the opposite side of the screw.

4: Mount the push rods to the two horns on the nozzle either via z-bend or some ballheads.

Now the whole Unit only needs to be mounted to your thrust tube and two servos have to be installed and you're done!

The unit works without the pin and I successfully landed several flights this way but now I mount it, and so should you, for the added level of security without adding any real weight!
